Introduction {#introduction}
=====================

RDF datasets support a default graph and zero or more **named graphs**, where each named graph is a pair of a **graph name** (an IRI or a blank node) and an RDF graph. [W3C](https://www.w3.org/TR/2025/WD-rdf12-concepts-20250225/)

However, RDF does not standardize a single formal semantics for *datasets as a whole*, and graph names are not given an agreed universal meaning beyond their structural role in the dataset. [W3C](https://www.w3.org/TR/rdf11-datasets/)

This specification defines a **minimal exchange pattern**: use named graphs as *units of assertion/context*, and use a triple in a *context graph* to indicate which *target graph* it contextualizes.

Conformance {#conformance}
===========

Conformance requirements are expressed with a combination of descriptive assertions and RFC 2119 terminology. 
The key words “MUST”, “MUST NOT”, “REQUIRED”, “SHALL”, “SHALL NOT”, “SHOULD”, “SHOULD NOT”, “RECOMMENDED”, “MAY”, 
and “OPTIONAL” in the normative parts of this document are to be interpreted as described in RFC 2119. However, 
for readability, these words do not appear in all uppercase letters in this specification.

All of the text of this specification is normative except sections explicitly marked as non-normative, examples, 
and notes. [[RFC2119]]

Terminology {#terminology}
===========

The following terminology is used throughout the specification document:

-   **Dataset**: An RDF dataset as defined in RDF Concepts. [W3C](https://www.w3.org/TR/2025/WD-rdf12-concepts-20250225/)
    
-   **Graph name**: The IRI or blank node that names a named graph in the dataset. [W3C](https://www.w3.org/TR/2025/WD-rdf12-concepts-20250225/)
    
-   **Target graph**: A named graph in the dataset that is the subject of contextual statements.
    
-   **Context graph**: A named graph that contains a `ca:aboutGraph` statement identifying a target graph.
    
-   **Graph reference**: An RDF term that is used as a graph name in the dataset (optionally skolemized; see [[#skolemids]]).
    

Data model and core idea {#datamodel}
===========

A **context association** is represented by:

1.  A **target named graph** `T` (graph name = `t`), containing data triples.
    
2.  A **context named graph** `C` (graph name = `c`), containing context triples, including the **anchor triple**:
    

> `c ca:aboutGraph t .`

This anchor makes the association **self-describing** and machine-discoverable without needing out-of-band conventions.

## 3.1. Minimal semantics (normative) ## {#minimalsemantics}

Given a dataset `D`:

-   If a named graph `C` in `D` contains the triple `(c, ca:aboutGraph, t)`, then `C` is a **context graph** and `t` is its **target graph reference**.
    
-   For processing under this specification, the **context statements** are all other triples in graph `C` (i.e., excluding the anchor triple).
    
-   The **context association** expresses that the context statements are intended to be interpreted *with respect to* the target named graph whose graph name is `t` **in the same dataset**.
    

This specification does **not** require that context statements entail the triples in the target graph being asserted in the default graph (i.e., no “automatic lifting” of triples).

Vocabulary (normative) {#vocabulary}
===========

All terms are in:

```turtle
@prefix ca: <https://w3id.org/context-associations#> .
```

## `ca:aboutGraph` ## {#aboutgraph}
 
-   **Type**: `rdf:Property`
    
-   **Intended meaning**: Links a context graph (by its graph name) to the graph name of its target graph.
    

**Constraint (normative):**

-   A context graph **MUST** contain **exactly one** `ca:aboutGraph` triple whose subject is the context graph’s own graph name.
    

(If you want multi-target context graphs later, that can be an extension profile, but “exactly one” keeps discovery + chaining simple.)

##Optional round-trip/import terms (non-normative but recommended) ## {#roundtripterms}

These are optional affordances for receivers who relabel graph identifiers on ingest:

-   `ca:sourceGraphName` — stores the **original** graph identifier from the sender (IRI or blank node label or skolem IRI).
    
-   `ca:assertedIn` — indicates that the target triples were originally asserted in some graph (including the default graph).
    
-   `ca:DefaultGraph` — a constant used as an object of `ca:assertedIn` to refer to the dataset default graph (since it has no RDF term name).
    

(These keep your “exchange first, local optimization later” story workable without bloating core semantics.)

Examples (informative) {#examples}
===================

## Simple metadata about a data graph (TriG) ## {#metadata}

TriG allows graph labels to be IRIs or blank nodes and allows them to reoccur in triples. [W3C](https://www.w3.org/TR/rdf12-trig/)

```turtle
@prefix ca: <https://w3id.org/context-associations#> .
@prefix : <https://example.org/ns#> .

_:data {
  <x> <y> <z> .
}

_:ctx {
  _:ctx ca:aboutGraph _:data .
  _:data :author <Bob> .
  _:data :retrievedFrom <https://source.example/> .
}
```

## Chaining (context about context) ## {#chaining}

```turtle
@prefix ca: <https://w3id.org/context-associations#> .
@prefix : <https://example.org/ns#> .

_:data { <x> <y> <z> . }

_:policy {
  _:policy ca:aboutGraph _:data .
  _:data :allowedPurpose :Analytics .
}

_:sig {
  _:sig ca:aboutGraph _:policy .
  _:policy :signatureValue "..." .
  _:policy :verificationKey <did:example:123#k1> .
}
```

Graph identifiers and exchange profiles {#identifiersandprofiles}
==============

## Blank node graph names (recommended default) ## {#blanknodenames}

Graph names MAY be blank nodes. RDF Concepts defines blank nodes as not identifying specific resources, and TriG permits blank nodes as graph labels. [W3C](https://www.w3.org/TR/rdf12-concepts/)

This specification **RECOMMENDS** using blank nodes for graph names participating in context associations when the goal is to avoid unintended co-reference/merge across unrelated datasets.

## Skolemized identifiers (optional) ## {#skolemids}

Implementations MAY replace blank nodes with Skolem IRIs, and systems doing so SHOULD mint globally unique IRIs for each blank node. [W3C](https://www.w3.org/2011/rdf-wg/wiki/Skolemisation)

Skolemization can improve addressability and compatibility with systems/protocols that require graph IRIs (e.g., Graph Store HTTP Protocol expects an IRI for each named graph). [W3C](https://www.w3.org/TR/sparql11-http-rdf-update/)

**Import guidance (non-normative):**

-   When importing datasets across untrusted boundaries, a receiver MAY relabel incoming skolem graph identifiers to fresh local identifiers to prevent accidental or adversarial co-reference, while preserving the sender identifier via `ca:sourceGraphName`.
    

Processing algorithm (normative) {#algorithm}
================

A conforming **CA processor** MUST implement the following:

1.  Parse the input as an RDF dataset.
    
2.  For each named graph `C` with graph name `c`, find triples `(c, ca:aboutGraph, t)` **within `C`**.
    
3.  If there is exactly one such triple, treat `C` as a context graph targeting `t`.
    
4.  The association output is a set of pairs `(c -> t)` plus the set of context triples in `C` excluding the anchor triple.
    
5.  A processor MUST NOT assume that `t` is globally meaningful outside the dataset scope unless an application profile explicitly says so (e.g., trusted skolem IDs).
    

Dataset Conformance {#datasetconformance}
====================

A dataset conforms to this specification if:

-   Every context graph contains exactly one anchor triple linking itself to its target graph via `ca:aboutGraph`.
    
-   The subject of `ca:aboutGraph` is identical to the context graph name.
    
-   The object of `ca:aboutGraph` is intended to denote a target graph name within the same dataset.
    

Interoperability notes (informative) {#notes}
=================

-   TriG and N-Quads are natural exchange syntaxes for context associations because they represent datasets and support blank node graph labels. [W3C](https://www.w3.org/TR/rdf12-trig/)
    
-   Systems that manage named graphs via Graph Store HTTP Protocol require graph IRIs; blank node graph names may need skolemization or local relabeling for such workflows. [W3C](https://www.w3.org/TR/sparql11-http-rdf-update/)
    

Security considerations (informative) {#security}
=================

-   If skolem graph identifiers are treated as globally authoritative, an attacker may attempt IRI collision to cause unintended merges. Consider relabel-on-ingest at trust boundaries (§6.2).
    
-   Context associations are compatible with signing, but signatures require canonicalization of RDF content (e.g., RDFC-1.0). This specification does not define a signature format. [W3C](https://www.w3.org/TR/rdf-canon/)
    